<br>
Background:  I am an introvert.  Roughly 10% of the American population are introverts, the other 90% are extroverts.  While I have noticed great patience on the part of an introvert concerning an exuberant extrovert, I have also noticed that a lot of extroverts do NOT understand that introverts just want to be left alone.<br>
<br>
I work as a security guard in a firm (a meat shield) that employs a lot of computer technicians, people I have always admired because there's no way in hell I can do what they do.  I am an English major - I dive headfirst into Shakespeare and Keats.  I am full-time college and work full-time, hence I am almost always studying at work.  If I have some rare time I read a novel for pure pleasure.<br>
<br>
Now ... this frequently happens ...<br>
<br>
Techie_01 stops by my desk on his way out the door.<br>
Techie_01:  Good night!<br>
Me:  (looks up from book, makes eye contact, smiles) Good night!<br>
Techie_01: Whatcha reading?<br>
Me: (holds up book to show him)  Shelley.<br>
Techie_01:  Who's that?<br>
Me:  A poet.<br>
Techie_01:  Oh.  Never heard of him.  (Which I always figure, since they are not English majors)<br>
Techie_01 Leaves.<br>
<br>
Now, don't get me wrong, I'm not a mean person, I always smile and make eye contact and so on.  But why do people feel the need to ask me what I'm reading?  When I'm reading a novel it's always this ...<br>
<br>
Techie_02:  Whatcha reading?<br>
Me:  (shows him the book)  Tolkien<br>
Techie_02:  Ohh...  Is it good?<br>
<br>
No, it's a pile of crap.  Tolkien is so putrescent that I can't believe I'm even holding the stinking, putrid book.  I'm forcing myself to do penance for eating that pint of Haagen-Daaz last night.  Of COURSE it's good, you freak!!  Why on earth would I read it if it wasn't??<br>
<br>
Someone please answer me this .. (or don't, it's a rant and I'm not looking for the answers :) .. Why do people feel the need to make inane, useless conversation?  Why can't they say &quot;Good night&quot; and leave?  Why do they have to obviously interrupt what I am doing to ask me something they don't even care about?  Why can't people just keep their mouths shut?<br>
<br>
Next topic:  Microwave popcorn.  I love it.  It's cheap, easy to make, delish, and fills me up.  Each and every time I make microwave popcorn at work, WHY do people (in droves, mind you) feel the need to walk by my desk and say:<br>
<br>
Employee_01:  That smells good!<br>
<br>
Why, yes.  It tastes good too.  Do you want it?  No?  Then shut the hell up!  Why would someone tell me my lunch smells good if they don't want some of it?  Just to make conversation?  You're not stopping to talk to me, just walking by.  Why do you have to open your mouth?  Just keep walking!  I'm busy reading my penance Tolkien!<br>
<br>
OK, all better now.<br>
<br>
Laogheire<br>
