<br>
Lao, personally, I'm offended by your comment. I've always been a straight "A" student since first grade. Now that I'm in college, I've majored in Biology, Psychology, and finally settled on Computer Science. I've never even thought about chosing English as a major simply because it didn't spark my interest. But does being a computer science major make me (or anyone in my field of study) too ignorant to know of fine writers such as Shakespeare, Tolkien, Shelley, Whitman, or Hemmingway? I would sure hope not. Who are you to judge that just because someone went to school for computers, are unfamiliar with poetry or other fine literature? Sure their emphasis was not in literary arts and perhaps does not have as strong a background as you, an English major have in it, but it doesn't mean they are not educated enough to not have clue about your field of study?<br>
<br>
English is a required course for all US universities, and I highly doubt that anyone with a college degree would've graduated without some sort of knowledge in fine English literature. I would assume that since you work for a computer firm that its employees would hold some sort of higher learning degree, since the computer industry has advanced to be quite a competitive field.<br>
<br>
There's nothing wrong with silence and wanting to keep to yourself.  As an extrovert, there are times when I want to be left alone. Sometimes, solitude is nice. That's why I played a druid back when I still played EQ.  It's for the times when I just wanted to have some alone time and not be bothered.  If I wanted to group, I had my cleric for that. So I can understand an introvert's desire to be left alone.<br>
<br>
If someone is unfamiliar with an author whose work you just so happen to be reading, why not spend 30 seconds of your life to educate them?  If the person insists on carrying on a conversation, just politely tell them, "I'm sorry but I must return to my studies."  You'd be amazed at how many friends you could make. Even the most introverted person can never have too many friends. :) <br>
<br>
